## LAW 4 — ProForm Usage

### 4.1 — Always Schema-Driven

All forms with ≥2 fields **MUST** use `<ProForm>` with a typed `FormSchema`.

```vue
<script setup lang="ts">
import type { FormSchema } from '@/components/ProForm'
import { useForm } from '@/components/ProForm'

const schema = reactive<FormSchema>({
  fields: [
    { name: 'username', component: 'input', label: 'Username', required: true, span: { xs: 12, md: 6 } },
    { name: 'role', component: 'select', label: 'Role', options: roleOptions, span: { xs: 12, md: 6 } },
    { name: 'email', component: 'input', label: 'Email', span: 12 },
  ],
})

const { handleSubmit } = useForm({ schema })
const onSubmit = handleSubmit(async (values) => { await saveUser(values) })
</script>

<template>
  <ProForm :schema="schema" @submit="onSubmit" />
</template>
```

### 4.2 — Responsive Grid via `span` (NOT UnoCSS grid)

ProForm uses an **internal 12-column CSS grid**. Control layout with the `span` prop on each field.

```typescript
// ✅ REQUIRED: responsive span
span: { xs: 12, md: 6, xl: 4 }   // full → half → third
span: 12                           // always full width
span: 6                            // always half width

// ❌ FORBIDDEN: UnoCSS grid classes on ProForm or its wrapper
// <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3">   ← do NOT wrap ProForm this way
// ProForm manages its 12-col CSS grid via span prop
```

### 4.3 — Schema File Rule

Forms with **>4 fields** MUST define schema in a separate file:

```
src/views/system/user/
├── index.vue
├── schemas/
│   └── userFormSchema.ts
└── hooks/
    └── useUserForm.ts
```

